Over 10 steps? A good PM routine can just have two steps (cleansing and moisturising)- but if you have skin concerns, you can add in a targeted product for that concern. I’m using finecea here which is an azelaic acid :) 

I cleansed off camera with the water bank cleanser from Laniege which is amazing 

Murad barrier cream on the sensitive areas on my face because it’s winter 🥶 and I adore my Lait-creme sensitive from embroliysse 

Part pr xx

Irritated eyelids on repeat, even though you’re being really careful? There could be heaps of reasons- but: If we’re mushing around the next skincare steps, there’s a decent chance the previous likes have travelled on our skin. Usually not the end of the world, but if we’re using a strong active, you might want to keep that away from sensitive spots 

@muradskincareaus @hq.hive pr

Pls don’t “not all Vit C” in the comments because ofcourse! There are great ones out there- and they might work for you. If they do- great! But 👀 I’d be so bold as to say I’ve seen lots of people do better with ingredients that suit their acne prone skin a bit better, and that’s something I’ve found too 🤍

I wish the girlies with pigmented acne scarring knew that when products say they work on “dark spots” it doesn’t always mean *our* kind of dark spots- and what helps *some* dark spots like sun spots or “age” spots can actually be too sensitising for us. 

Eg: Vit C usually works amazing for babes wanting to lighten sun spots, but not always great for acne prone skin

Juicy blushes that fight weather-induced dullness (plus, they’re gorgeous multi-taskers in my opinion)

I’ve often felt I’m balancing between a hydrated glowy look and reducing the appearance of the texture that feels more apparent in winter- these picks strike a balance between both- and in time work to improve the appearance of the areas they’re applied to. 

Pretty darn fantastic! Full write up linked in @whiterabbitsocial_ bio, but swipe through to read some cute illustrations 👉

Words by: @minnieisaac_ 

Ps: let us know if you like skincare makeup hybrids, if there are any ingredients you hate seeing- or if there are picks we have to try.

Review time 👀 Do you use a tinted brow gel? They’re harder to get right than you think 🤔 This is the brow fluff from @maybelline and I’ve been testing and trialing a few ways 

I likey! It hasn’t dethroned my benefit gimme brow, but considering it’s about $12AUD it ticks the boxes for pigment level (not too pigmented so it doesn’t get messy) + nice and matte w/ no crunch 

Doesn’t overly deposit product etc 🙏

So yes! I recommend trying if you’re on the market for one :) I’m using shade “deep brown” 

It comes in 4 shades in Aus, but 6 in the US- none of them seem to run too warm which is good 

Pr xx #brows #review #maybelline #browgel #makeup #browfluff

Review is here 🥳 of the Tumeric Brightening mask from @cropskincare 

It’s really important to note you can’t enjoy and use Tumeric in your skincare without having a reflection of what aspects we engage with from other cultures- and making sure they’re getting the credit they deserve- esp when lots of feelings about diversity seem to be pushed back. 

Tumeric has been used for thousands of years in south east Asia in food, skin products and even medicine 🥰 and should be celebrated. 

I’ve been seeing this a lot with matcha lately too, or even gifting money at weddings- when other cultures have been loving and using the ingredients for generations- or doing a particular practise for generations 

Let’s remember the roots of the beautiful ingredients were starting to embrace in the west! And not reject everything else about a culture besides what we like in skincare. 

Because real talk seeing actual ra*ists enjoy matcha and tumeric in their skincare and lattes is making me want to do a back flip (not in a happy way) xx 

#Tumeric #Indian #SouthEastAsia #SouthAsian
